thors assert the central place of sex workers in discussions about their lives and work. This book opposes discourses that position sex workers as victims without agency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHuman trafficking. 0aProstitutesxCivil rights. 0aProstitution. 0aVictims of crimes. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Prostitution & Sex Trade.2bisacsh1 aBruckert, Chris, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBruckert, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorriveau, Patrice, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCorriveau, Patrice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMensah, Maria Nengeh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParent, Colette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoth, Käthe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToupin, Louise, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aToupin, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077482613640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774826136423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774826136/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles